[Handwritten letter on plain white paper with blue ink]
[At top in pencil: "Suchblad, Jane [1956]"]
[Transcriber's Note: Based on her writing style, her surname could be "Sundblad" instead of Suchblad]
Dear Mr. Conroy, I am writing to thank you very sincerely for the kind book that arrived to-day - it is with great pleasure that I look forward to reading thru.  "American humans" so easily gets labelled that way without any effort to trace its further origins - I must confess I had no idea that James Thurber wasn't a New Yorker. - That's the first friend I have made, just by
Completed

[Image 2 or 2]
[Handwritten letter on plain white paper with blue ink]
[Transcriber's Note: Based on her writing style, her surname could be "Sundblad" instead of Suchblad]
looking at your list, and I am sure there are a lot more.  Thank you so very much!  Sincerely Jane Sundblad.
Evanston, May 28th 1956.
2020 Orrington.
Completed

[Image 1 of 2]
[Handwritten letter on gold company stationary with black ink]
ALAN SWALLOW * PUBLISHER
The Swallow Press * Sage Books * Big Mountain Press
2679 SOUTH YORK : DENVER 10 COLORADO
12/15/63 [December 15, 1963]
Dear Jack, Thanks for your letter.  Glad that Colliers + Fisher arrived and are being reviewed.  Since you admired the [unclear - Under Hunter Tet], you should know what happened to it.  I'm sending you a copy (somewhat dogeared) of Orphans in Gethsemane - 12th volume with the Testament of Man, and a rewriting of the Tet and continuing it as to the present.  Also, as you see by full list I do have April.  Are the things I get in bringing out Laxton Fisher
Completed

[Image 2 of 2]
[Handwritten letter on gold company stationary with black ink]
materials.  It is my wife's favorite among the Fisher novels.  Cordially, Alan
Completed
Hi, Jack!  Thank you for the Christmas greetings.  Happy new year from us all!  Sincerely, Togo
Completed

[Image 1 of 4]
[Plain gray parchment paper handwritten in black ink]
DOUGLAS TAYLOR
39 GUESSENS RD.
WELWYN GARDEN CITY
HERTS ENGLAND.
23 9 1965 [23 September 1965]
Dear Mr. Jack Conroy,
Hallo to you.  Well Mr. U.S.A. please do not have a heart attack on receipt of this letter from a Kiwi known to you for a few minutes at an South Kensington Hotel.  Although I have never received an answer to my letter of early October thanking you for your kind gift of your novel, "The Disinherited."  It is a grand novel and several of my friends have enjoyed your book.  Have
Completed

[Image 2 of 4]
[Plain gray parchment paper handwritten in black ink]
you had any further successes?  Since my last letter from London I have changed my position.  I am employed by an American firm as an Inspector of Equipment for the production of grinding stones.  The firm is known as Norton Abrasives of the U.S.A.  This week I have had a holiday because all days owing must be taken before the end of September.  I have had a very busy week because I have been attending three departments of immigration, The U.S.A., Canada & Rhodesia.  I have great difficulty with your country
Completed

[Image 3 of 4]
[Plain gray parchment paper handwritten in black ink]
because of my age and not having a position to go to.  I would like to give you a few details concerning myself and maybe you could be kind enough to advise me if I could have and prospects in the land of all nations (USA).
No1  Age 52
Height  5'-10-1/2"
Weight 170 lbs
My trade is wood machinist and wood turner.  I have had experience as air frame filter salesman in the Soft Furnishing trade for 10 years.  Five years as a clerical man in a large hospital in Johannesburg and several
Completed

[Image 4 of 4]
[Plain gray parchment paper handwritten in black ink]
other position during the long years of travel.  Not a very exciting history to relate. Well Mr. Conroy enough said about myself.  I am sending you a photo of myself taken in Venice.  Maybe you can recall the face.  Cheerio Mr. U.S.A. and please forgive my poor style.  I am not a great writer.  Please answer my scrawl if you can find the time.  Yours, Douglas.  Regards to your wife
Completed

[Image 1 of 1]
[Handwritten letter on white stationary with black pen]
Dear Jack - Am enclosing the note Dorothy Schmidt sent to us.  Your books made a tremendous hit with their boys as well as with Dorothy and Paul.  I knew they would.  I'm glad we could send such fine books to such wonderful friends.  Thanks again for the autographs - they made a hit too.  Affectionately, Ida Terkel  See you Sat.
Completed

[Image 1 of 2]
[Plain faded white post card handwritten in blue ink, printed with red lettering "THIS SIDE OF CARD IS FOR ADDRESS," with a red printed UNITED STATES POSTAL CARD 2 CENTS stamp containing sketched image of Benjamin Franklin, and postmarked CHICAGO, ILL,. JUL 29, 1953.]
[Studs Terkel is the author.]
Mr. JACK CONROY
6012 S. Green Street
Chicago, ILLINOIS
Completed

[Image 2 of 2]
[Plain faded white postcard handwritten in blue ink]
["TERKEL" handwritten in red pencil in the upper right corner.]
Dear Jack:
A magnificent protest to WENR - it was forwarded to me.  Got about 300 letters - there were 70 phone calls when Eug'ene came on - 69 pro-Terkel.  The other was a personal friend of Eug'ene's.  I think he wears BLUE pajamas, too.
Am starting a new radio show Aug. [August] 4 - WENR - 11:30 PM-1:00 AM - "Sound of the City."  Will try to keep it good.  Heard great reports about your appearance on WFMT.
My best to family -
Studs -
[TRANSCRIBER'S NOTE:  A search of the online Studs Terkel Radio Archive at https://studsterkel.wfmt.com/program-search?query=eugene&sort_by=title&sort_order=DESC reveals that the person referenced in this letter may be Eug'ene Ionesco who Studs knew and interviewed several times over the years . . . Studs used the acute accented 'e both times when referring to him.]
Completed

[Image 2 of 3]
[Letter printed on stationary of WFMT 500 NORTH MICHIGAN AVENUE CHICAGO ILLINOIS 60611 - CHICAGO'S FINE ARTS STATION/98.7 - STUDS TERKEL (312) 751-7125]
Dear Professor (Himself) Conroy:  What a delight to hear from the one and only - the friend of the fell - the sage of Moberly!  I have been thinking often of you - and am hoping you are working on your memoirs.  Friend - such a Win Stracke Chicago's answer to Chaliapin - tell me you are your fine, ebullient self. (over)
Completed

[Image 3 of 3]
[Letter plain stationary with no printed markings]
- 2 -  Of course, I'll have my book sent to you at once.  "Food Killer" looks fine.  Am knocking myself out here with too much to do - if we ever get together one day soon - Gladys and I will do "Careless Love" and you, naturally will offer "The Baggage Coach Ahead."  Ida and I send our love to Gladys and you.  Studs (Louie)
Completed

[Image 1 of 1]
[Handwritten in pencil at the top right: "Terkel, Ida"]
[Holiday greeting printed with red ink on a white card]
Happy Holidays
Meilleurs Voeux
Felices Fiestas
C HOBbIM TOAOM
[Handwritten in blue ink]
1/2/80
Dear Conroys -
We loved your holiday note.  We're right, Studs will soon review the Jack Conroy Reader, which he likes very much, for the Sun Times.
A while back he did a marvelous WFMT interview with Stephen Wade, a truly talented original.  How great to know this guy use[d] your material.
Love to both of you and a Happy '80 - The Terkels
Completed

[Image 1 of 1]
[Handwritten in pencil at the top right: "Terkel, Studs and Ida"]
[Handwritten in blue ink on plain white paper]
1/20/81
Dear Jack and Gladys:
A very belated, but heartfelt Holiday greeting!  Watching the old ritual today wonder what the coming year holds for us.  Heard a friend say that an orangutan could have beat Carter.  The reply was that one did.
How are you both?  Are your memoirs coming out soon, Jack?  Heard they were in the works.
Best to both of you - Love from Studs and me
Ida T.
Completed

Dear Jack + Gladys:  We're here in this former whaling port where Melville beached himself, where Twain in his 20's dodged his newspaper correspondent's duties for six lost weeks, where the humpback whales come to mate.  Magical.  Have a good New Year.  Love, David + Patt Wagoner
